description.narrative: (Jamaica): USAID/Jamaica will use FY 2017 funds to transition community-based activities that increase the capacity of communities and local governance systems to adapt to droughts, floods, and hurricanes, to GOJ and civil society actors. Projects initiated by USAID/Jamaica in this area are based on the premise that prevention ahead of a disaster saves lives, and are vastly more cost efficient compared to post-disaster response. USAID helps the Jamaican government to integrate disaster risk reduction into planning and improve policies that improve coordination. Community members are trained in improved planning, disaster risks and response, and building social cohesion while promoting resilient livelihoods. By consolidating activities and formulating a comprehensive exit strategy, this investment will sustain gains made in disaster risk reduction, community resilience and improved planning practices, which increase stability and security in Jamaica.
